meta {
  name: 48 Create User Flow (E2E)
  seq: 48
}

docs {
  # Create User Flow (E2E)

  A single, self-contained, top-to-bottom run that provisions a **brand-new
  order-capable staff user**, logs in as that user, and then walks the front-desk
  **Registration** phase (register a patient → create an order) **as the new
  user**. Each request feeds the ids/tokens it captures into the next — select
  the **Local** environment and **Run Folder** (or send each request in `seq`
  order); no manual edits are needed.

  ## What "a user who can create orders" means here

  Order creation is a front-desk (**Registration**) capability. The role that
  carries it out of the box is **`receptionist`** — a **branch-level** role whose
  permission baseline includes `patient:create` + `order:create` (via the
  `sales` module: `sales:view`/`sales:write`/`sales:edit`). So the flow:

  1. **Enables** the `registration` + `sales` modules on the branch (a branch
     assignment may only use modules that are enabled + valid for the branch
     type — DIAGNOSTIC/OPD/IPD/PHARMACY/COMBINED all offer both).
  2. **Creates** the user with `roleKey: receptionist` and a branch assignment
     (`role: receptionist`, `modules: [registration, sales]`,
     `defaultModule: registration`, `defaultBranch: true`). The `receptionist`
     role template links **both** `registration` and `sales`, so either is a
     valid landing `defaultModule`.
  3. **Grants** the `registration` + `sales` module permissions explicitly per
     (user + branch) so both the create-order capability and the **Registration
     tab visibility** are present regardless of role baseline.
  4. **Logs in** as the new user and (because `receptionist` is branch-level)
     lands on a **branch-scoped** JWT — exactly what `POST /orders` needs
     (it reads the active branch from the token, never the body).

  > **FE module visibility (kaltros-fe):** the front-end reveals a module's
  > tab/route only when `GET /users/manage/me/permissions` reports it as
  > `moduleAllowed` for the active branch. `registration` is therefore a
  > **permission-bearing** module (it backs the built `/registration` page) and
  > sits in the `receptionist` role baseline — so this user sees the Registration
  > module. (An "enablement-only" module with no permission keys can never be
  > `moduleAllowed`, so it would stay hidden — which is why `registration` mints
  > standard permissions.)

  > **Note on RBAC enforcement (CLAUDE.md §8):** business routes are
  > authenticated but do **not** yet enforce per-permission RBAC at the route
  > level — permissions are resolved as *data* for the frontend + a future guard.
  > So the functional requirement to create an order today is a **branch-scoped**
  > business JWT. Steps 3 + 5 still set the role/permissions correctly so the
  > user is provisioned exactly as the product intends (and stays correct once
  > the guard lands).

  ## Fully automated — just click Send

  Every request has a `script:post-response` that stores what it captures as
  **runtime variables** via `bru.setVar(...)`; every dependent request reads them
  via `{{...}}`. The only pre-request values you supply are the **admin login
  creds** in step 1 (`adminPhone` / `adminTempPassword` / `tenantSlug`) — the
  same ones the rest of the collection uses. Auto-captured variables:

  `businessAccessToken` (admin, then swapped to the new user in step 6),
  `businessRefreshToken`, `tenantId`, `branchId`, `newUserId`, `newUserCode`,
  `newUserLoginIdentifier`, `branchLabTestId`, `branchLabPanelId`, `patientId`,
  `orderId`.

  ## Prerequisites

  - The backend is running (`pnpm start:dev` in `kalnostics-new/`) with Postgres
    and a **seeded tenant** whose `business_admin` login creds are in the `Local`
    environment (`adminPhone` / `adminTempPassword` / `tenantSlug`).
  - The tenant has a **main branch** whose type offers `registration` + `sales`
    (DIAGNOSTIC/OPD/IPD/PHARMACY/COMBINED — the seeded main lab is DIAGNOSTIC).
  - The branch already has an **imported catalogue** (at least one active Branch
    Lab Test / Panel) so the registration order has items to reference. Run
    **47 Order Flow (E2E)** (or **32 / 33** import steps) once beforehand if the
    branch is empty — steps 8-9 list & capture whatever is there.
  - The backend has `registration` as a **permission-bearing** module (see the
    FE-access note above). Step 7 asserts this; if it fails, restart the backend.

  ## Steps

  1. **Admin Login** — authenticate as `business_admin` (the provisioning actor).
  2. **Get Main Branch** — resolve `branchId`.
  3. **Enable Branch Modules** — enable `registration` + `sales` on the branch.
  4. **Create Order-Capable User** — `receptionist` + branch assignment
     (`modules: [registration, sales]`, `defaultModule: registration`).
  5. **Grant Order Permissions** — explicit `registration:*` + `sales:*` grants.
  6. **Login as New User** — swap the working token to the new user (branch-scoped).
  7. **Verify Registration Access** — call `me/permissions` (the exact endpoint
     kaltros-fe uses) and assert Registration is visible for this user.
  8-11. **Registration phase** — list branch catalogue → create patient → create
     order, all **as the new user**.

  ## Chain of captured variables

  Admin Login → admin `businessAccessToken` · Get Main Branch → `branchId` ·
  Enable Branch Modules → — · Create User → `newUserId` + `newUserCode` +
  `newUserLoginIdentifier` · Grant Order Permissions → — · **Login as New User**
  → new-user `businessAccessToken` (branch-scoped) · Verify Registration Access →
  — · List Branch Lab Test → `branchLabTestId` · List Branch Lab Panel →
  `branchLabPanelId` · Create Patient → `patientId` · **Create Order** → `orderId`.

  Full user CRUD lives in **06 Users**; full order CRUD in **42 Orders**.
}
